ural Alternatives -- t11. Harlem Schools in the Fiscal Crisis -- t12. Pursuing “Real Power to Parents”: Babette Edwards’s Activism from Community Control to Charter Schools -- t13. Teaching Harlem: Black Teachers and the Changing Educational Landscape of Twenty- First-Century Central Harlem -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of the twentieth century, education was a key site for envisioning opportunities for African Americans, but the very schools they attended sometimes acted as obstacles to black flourishing. Educating Harlem brings together a multidisciplinary group of scholars to provide a broad consideration of the history of schooling in perhaps the nation’s most iconic black community.The volume traces the varied ways that Harlem residents defined and pursued educational justice for their children and community despite consistent neglect and structural oppression. Contributors investigate the individuals, organizations, and initiatives that fostered educational visions, underscoring their breadth, variety, and persistence. Their essays span the century, from the Great Migration and the Harlem Renaissance through the 1970s fiscal crisis and up to the present. They tell the stories of Harlem residents from a wide variety of social positions and life experiences, from young children to expert researchers to neighborhood mothers and ambitious institution builders who imagined a dynamic array of possibilities from modest improvements to radical reshaping of their schools. Representing many disciplinary perspectives, the chapters examine a range of topics including architecture, literature, film, youth and adult organizing, employment, and city politics. Challenging the conventional rise-and-fall narratives found in many urban histories, the book tells a story of persistent struggle in each phase of the twentieth century. Educating Harlem paints a nuanced portrait of education in a storied community and brings much-needed historical context to one of the most embattled educational spaces today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in educationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in educationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool improvement programszNew York (State)zNew York. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aCyna, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, Ansley T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, Ansley T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGutman, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbison, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Kimberley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuravich, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKridel, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewer, Brittney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrell, Ernest, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrell, Ernest, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerlstein, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerrillo, Jonna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips-Fein, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c